Here is an example of how we could achieve the best of both worlds.  We offer methods directly lifted from Array that do exactly what their native counterparts do and we offer alternates that do things functionally without mutation.  (Again, as illustrated above -- in the argument processing example -- having mutating functions can prove useful.)

```
// included detach which is handy in general but especially so in this situation
_.detach = function(fn){ //extract an object function for general use
  return function(obj){
    return fn.apply(obj, _.rest(arguments));
  }
}

_.concat = _.detach(Array.prototype.concat);

_.unshift = _.detach(Array.prototype.unshift);

_.prepend = function(list, item){ //instead of unshift if you don't want the new length
  return [item].concat(list);
}

_.push = _.detach(Array.prototype.push);

_.append = function(list, item){ //instead of push if you don't want the new length
  return list.concat([item]);
}

_.pop = _.detach(Array.prototype.pop); //instead of initial if mutation is desired

_.shift = _.detach(Array.prototype.shift) //instead of rest if mutation is desired

_.reverse = _.detach(Array.prototype.reverse);

_.backward = _.compose(_.reverse, _.clone); //instead of reverse if mutation is undesired

_.join = _.detach(Array.prototype.join);

_.sort = _.detach(Array.prototype.sort);

_.sorted = _.compose(_.sort, _.clone); //instead of sort if mutation is undesired

_.splice = _.detach(Array.prototype.splice);

_.ammend = function(list, idx, removeCount){ //instead of splice if mutation is undesired
  var additions = Array.prototype.slice.call(arguments, 3);
  return _.slice(list, 0, idx).concat(additions).concat(_.slice(list, idx));
}

_.slice = _.detach(Array.prototype.slice);
```

See #1166 for `attach` which is the counterpart to `detach`.

